789,IssuesEvent,2015-10-05 14:03:40+00:00,10155460,dbader/schedule,611122,tdhopper,,,opened,Extend `schedule` to work as a decorator,[],[],0,"I would love to see `schedule` extended to work as a decorator. I envision syntax along the lines of 

```
@schedule.every().hour.do
def job():
    print(""I'm working..."")
```

When thinking through this, I found that this syntax:

```
import schedule
import time

dec = schedule.every(2).seconds.do

@dec
def job():
    print(""I'm working..."")
```
works already. 

Parentheses aren't allowed in decorators. (I think this is a result of [Guido's gut feeling](https://mail.python.org/pipermail/python-dev/2004-August/046711.html).) Syntax along the lines of this would be permitted: `@schedule.every.seconds.do`. 

Maybe it'd be insane, but we could implement something like `@schedule.every.ten.seconds.do`. There's probably a clever way to make that work for a large number of cases. Though, it doesn't resolve the issue of hard coding times.

Some discussion would be helpful before anyone tries implementing this.",{},{}
