1245,IssuesEvent,2016-04-07 15:02:43+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,843444,dpkp,,,closed,Possible typo in example JSON-serializing KafkaProducer,[],[],2,"I was trying out your library today and noticed that the following example from the README uses ```json.loads``` as the serializer (instead of ```json.dumps``` as I'd expect).

```
>>> # Serialize json messages
>>> import json
>>> producer = KafkaProducer(value_serializer=json.loads)
>>> producer.send('fizzbuzz', {'foo': 'bar'})
```
While trying it out, I noticed that using ```json.loads``` as in the original example results in nothing appearing on my active consumers, but replacing it with ```json.dumps``` causes the consumers to display the messages.

(Disclaimer: I'm extremely new to Kafka, so this may be a misunderstanding on my part of how it's supposed to delimit messages. I'm using both KafkaConsumer from your library with a json.loads deserializer and the test Kafka console consumer from the Kafka quickstart documentation.)",{},{}
1273,IssuesEvent,2015-07-02 15:46:04+00:00,21240523,glennmatthews/cot,5603551,glennmatthews,,,closed,add wildcarding for network names,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/glennmatthews/cot/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],0,"Similar to NIC names, it would be nice to be able to use a wildcard for network names:

    cot edit-hardware foo.ova --nic-networks ""mgmt0"" ""Ethernet1_{1}""

If we want to be crazy we could also support this for `--mac-addresses-list` and `--serial-connectivity`",{},{}
1283,IssuesEvent,2016-07-31 10:10:11+00:00,2675994,jamescasbon/PyVCF,15814544,Redmar-van-den-Berg,,,opened,Genotype level filters not supported,[],[],0,"Next to the normal FILTER, vcf files can also contain per-genotype filters, using the FT annotation in the FORMAT field. The format mimics the formatting of the FILTER field, eg 'PASS' for passing the filter, and 'filt1;filt2' for failing two filters.

From the VCFv4.2 spec:

> FT : sample genotype filter indicating if this genotype was “called” (similar in concept to the FILTER field). Again, use PASS to indicate that all filters have been passed, a semi-colon separated list of codes for filters that fail, or ‘.’ to indicate that filters have not been applied. These values should be described in the meta-information in the same way as FILTERs (String, no white-space or semi-colons permitted)

For now, PyVCF treats the FT annotation as a regular annotation instead of as a filter. I would like to add support for the FT annotation, and will post a pull request when I have a working implementation.",{},{}
