3133,IssuesEvent,2016-07-14 15:23:42+00:00,5816230,michiya/django-pyodbc-azure,1220698,kdazzle,,,opened,Accessing tables in a schema doesn't seem to work,[],[],0,"I'm not too familiar with MSSQL, so let me know if any terminology is wrong, but is there a supported way to access tables within a schema? For example, say I have a database and there is a schema called `Products`, and that schema contains a table `Coats`.

So I set up my Django model:

```
class Coat(models.Model):
    
    # attributes...

    class Meta:
        is_managed = False
        db_table = 'Coats'  # This is the tricky part
````

There doesn't seem like there is any good way to set the `db_table`. I've tried `Coats`, `Products.Coats`, `COATS`, `Products/Coats`, etc. etc.

However, there is a gross way to make it work that I found [here](http://kozelj.org/django-1-6-mssql-and-schemas/), which uses string injection. So using that, we'd set `db_table = 'Products].[Coats'`. 

Surely someone has faced this before - is there a better way to access tables in a schema? If not, maybe I can submit a PR to institutionalize this method because it was tough to even find a workaround for.

Thanks!",{},{}
