4514,IssuesEvent,2018-08-07 17:39:31+00:00,2640766,astropy/photutils,346587,eteq,847984,astropy,opened,Aperture photometry tables act like scalar apertures with length-1 list,"[{'id': 100230793, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMDAyMzA3OTM=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/astropy/photutils/labels/aperture', 'name': 'aperture', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}, {'id': 10561147, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMDU2MTE0Nw==', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/astropy/photutils/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'eb6420', 'default': True}]",[],0,"Some behavior pointed out to me by @hcferguson that I think is counter-intuitive and should change.  First, the part that *does* make sense:

```python
#setup
>>> im = np.random.randn(100,100)
>>> ap = photutils.CircularAperture((50,50),5)

>>> photutils.aperture_photometry(im, ap).colnames
['id', 'xcenter', 'ycenter', 'aperture_sum']
>>> photutils.aperture_photometry(im, [ap, ap]).colnames
['id', 'xcenter', 'ycenter', 'aperture_sum_0', 'aperture_sum_1']
```
So far so good. But then the following:
```python
>>> photutils.aperture_photometry(im, [ap]).colnames
['id', 'xcenter', 'ycenter', 'aperture_sum']
```
`aperture_sum` does not have an ``_0``!  This is very counter-intuitive, as normally a distinction is drawn between ""scalar"" and ""list/array/whatever of length 1"". 

I'd classify this as a bug and can just be fixed - do you agree @larrybradley ?  It does have potential backwards-compatibility concerns, but still... This is a thing that trips up enough novice users (the length-1 vs scalar distinction) that I think it's worth it.",{},{}
4566,IssuesEvent,2018-07-06 11:38:09+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,1914750,abmar,897180,scikit-image,opened,missing term in the definition of _cv_delta,[],[],0,"https://github.com/scikit-image/scikit-image/blob/acf8dad8529bdda3f8ae658fa31511843aa70389/skimage/segmentation/_chan_vese.py#L63

should read
```python
return  1/np.pi * eps / (eps**2 + x**2)
```",{},{}
