6368,IssuesEvent,2016-06-13 17:16:05+00:00,36759907,graphistry/pygraphistry,4249447,lmeyerov,6157633,graphistry,opened,Guide users with invalid certificates towards certificate_validation=False,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/graphistry/pygraphistry/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/graphistry/pygraphistry/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '159818'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/graphistry/pygraphistry/labels/p3', 'name': 'p3', 'color': '009800'}]",[],0,"Some users, for reasons out of their control, have invalid certificates. For example, they may deem their certificates secure/sufficient for internal reasons (e.g., cannot expose DNS), but still fail the underlying checks. Our workaround for `https` is `certificate_validation=False`. However, it is non-obvious for them to use this.

Ideas:

1. Make a FAQ section in `pygraphistry` with that as a hint

2. Improve the error message to provide that as a hint. Currently, what users see is `SSLError: bad handshake: Error([('SSL routines', 'SSL3_GET_SERVER_CERTIFICATE', 'certificate verify failed')],)`.

Other ideas?",{},{}
