7142,IssuesEvent,2017-06-26 18:11:34+00:00,41756998,pytest-dev/pytest-xdist,1085180,nicoddemus,8897583,pytest-dev,closed,Incorrect failure message attribute in junitxml file when combined with xdist,"[{'id': 255239944, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pytest-dev/pytest-xdist/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}]",[],9,"When combining xdist with pytest's junitxml flag there is an issue where the generated report will have the incorrect <failure message=> attribute value. 

test_case.py

```python
import pytest

class TestxDistXmlIssue:
    def test_one(self):
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        assert 1 == 2, ""Only print this message""

    def test_two(self):
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        assert False, ""Only print this message""
```

Ran with the following command

```
pytest -n2 --junitxml=""test_xdist.xml"" test_case.py
```

test_xdist.xml 

Notice that the <failure message=> attribute is a duplication of the stack trace 

```xml
<?xml version=""1.0"" encoding=""utf-8""?>
<testsuite errors=""0"" failures=""2"" name=""pytest"" skips=""0"" tests=""2"" time=""0.283"">
    <testcase classname=""pytesting.test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue"" file=""pytesting/test_case.py"" line=""25"" name=""test_two"" time=""0.0014913082122802734"">
        <failure message=""self = &lt;test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue object at 0x7f3770d5fa90&gt;      def test_two(self):         # stack trace code         # stack trace code         # stack trace code         # stack trace code         # stack trace code &gt;       assert False, &quot;Only print this message&quot; E       AssertionError: Only print this message E       assert False  pytesting/test_case.py:32: AssertionError"">self = &lt;test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue object at 0x7f3770d5fa90&gt;

    def test_two(self):
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
&gt;       assert False, &quot;Only print this message&quot;
E       AssertionError: Only print this message
E       assert False

pytesting/test_case.py:32: AssertionError</failure>
    </testcase>
    <testcase classname=""pytesting.test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue"" file=""pytesting/test_case.py"" line=""17"" name=""test_one"" time=""0.0014431476593017578"">
        <failure message=""self = &lt;test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue object at 0x7fab8351fac8&gt;      def test_one(self):         # stack trace code         # stack trace code         # stack trace code         # stack trace code         # stack trace code &gt;       assert 1 == 2, &quot;Only print this message&quot; E       AssertionError: Only print this message E       assert 1 == 2  pytesting/test_case.py:24: AssertionError"">self = &lt;test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue object at 0x7fab8351fac8&gt;

    def test_one(self):
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
&gt;       assert 1 == 2, &quot;Only print this message&quot;
E       AssertionError: Only print this message
E       assert 1 == 2

pytesting/test_case.py:24: AssertionError</failure>
    </testcase>
</testsuite>
```

If we take off the -n2 flag to disable xdist we get the expected faliure message attribute in the report

test_no_xdist.xml

```xml
<?xml version=""1.0"" encoding=""utf-8""?>
<testsuite errors=""0"" failures=""2"" name=""pytest"" skips=""0"" tests=""2"" time=""0.024"">
    <testcase classname=""pytesting.test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue"" file=""pytesting/test_case.py"" line=""17"" name=""test_one"" time=""0.0010428428649902344"">
        <failure message=""AssertionError: Only print this message assert 1 == 2"">self = &lt;test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue object at 0x7f63ae6656d8&gt;

    def test_one(self):
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
&gt;       assert 1 == 2, &quot;Only print this message&quot;
E       AssertionError: Only print this message
E       assert 1 == 2

pytesting/test_case.py:24: AssertionError</failure>
    </testcase>
    <testcase classname=""pytesting.test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue"" file=""pytesting/test_case.py"" line=""25"" name=""test_two"" time=""0.00023293495178222656"">
        <failure message=""AssertionError: Only print this message assert False"">self = &lt;test_case.TestxDistXmlIssue object at 0x7f63ae665358&gt;

    def test_two(self):
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
        # stack trace code
&gt;       assert False, &quot;Only print this message&quot;
E       AssertionError: Only print this message
E       assert False

pytesting/test_case.py:32: AssertionError</failure>
    </testcase>
</testsuite>
```

I believe the culprit is related to append_failure (line 133) in junitxml.py. When xdist is active that message is not being set to the expected longrepr.reprcrash.message value.

Additional information
ubuntu 14.04 python 3.6.0
Pip list
apipkg (1.4)
appdirs (1.4.3)
execnet (1.4.1)
packaging (16.8)
pip (9.0.1)
py (1.4.32)
pyparsing (2.2.0)
pytest (3.0.6)
pytest-xdist (1.15.0)
setuptools (34.3.1)
six (1.10.0)",{},{}
7151,IssuesEvent,2017-03-18 21:26:13+00:00,36279339,pytest-dev/pytest-selenium,1796208,birdsarah,8897583,pytest-dev,opened,Problem reading `--variables` from pytest.ini if `--driver-path` specified,[],[],0,"Not sure how best to investigate this or if this is even a pytest selenium problem.

On Windows 10.

I have a pytest.ini file

```
[pytest]
addopts = --variables=variables.json
```

If I run the following (with chromedriver available on the path):

    $ py.test --base-url www.google.com --driver Chrome

Then the `variables.json` is picked up correctly. 
   
However, if I run the following:

    $ py.test --base-url www.google.com --driver Chrome --driver-path ..\..\..\WebDrivers\chromedriver.exe

Then `variables.json` is not picked up for the variables option.

Finally though, if I add `--variables variables.json` into the call then it does work:

    $ py.test --base-url www.google.com --driver Chrome --driver-path ..\..\..\WebDrivers\chromedriver.exe --variables variables.json


",{},{}
7153,IssuesEvent,2018-08-16 11:30:13+00:00,16889277,pytest-dev/pytest-splinter,427136,bubenkoff,8897583,pytest-dev,closed,Support per test capabilities,[],[],2,"We are currently interested in using Zalenium and Browserstack to provide the Selenium grid which our tests can use. This brings us new requirements on how the browser capabilities are defined and the browser session lifecycle to enable us to set the test name and possibly also the success/failure status.

Rather than a single session scoped capability set, we need to have per test capabilities, parametrized with the test name.

Currently most fixtures have session scope and are used to build another session-scoped ``browser_instance_getter`` fixture that is then used to instantiate the test-scoped browser session, effectively capturing the browser kwargs and the capabilities in the session scope. So a wide refactoring seems to be needed to change this.

While we are at it it would be a plus to provide also some execution hook before the session is closed that could mark the test status (via setting a special cookie to Zalenium).

I am somewhat interested in developing this myself, but I feel it would need quite a change of the codebase and I am not sure how to tackle it without breaking too much.",{},{}
