8062,IssuesEvent,2018-07-12 14:10:20+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,6958867,dorodnic,14095512,IntelRealSense,closed,"""Sparse"" alignment image upscaling?","[{'id': 288064118, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyODgwNjQxMTg=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/IntelRealSense/librealsense/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}]","[{'login': 'RealSense-Customer-Engineering', 'id': 34384799, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjM0Mzg0Nzk5', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/34384799?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/RealSense-Customer-Engineering', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/RealSense-Customer-Engineering/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",3,"Hi again, I'm sort-of misusing the issue tracker as a forum now, feel free to close if not intended :-)

That being said, I noticed that e.g. when using `rs::stream::depth_aligned_to_color` at a higher color resolution, you get a ""sparse"" image. This is, of course, expected as https://github.com/IntelRealSense/librealsense/blob/master/src/image.cpp#L356 only maps one single source pixel to a single target pixel.

In `libfreenect2`, we had implemented a naive-but-mostly-sufficient nearest-neighbor upscaling procedure for this case so that you can get a dense, color-aligned depth image. Would you be interested in a PR implementing a similar behaviour for `librealsense`? Then I'll prepare one.
",{},{}
